
[1]scowl

   SCOWL, v.i. [Gr. to twist.]

   1. To wrinkle the brows, as in frowning or displeasure; to put on a
   frowning look; to look sour, sullen, severe or angry.

   She scowl'd and frown'd with froward countenance.

   2. To look gloomy, frowning, dark or tempestuous; as the scowling
   heavens.

                SCOWL, v.t. To drive with a scowl or frowns.

                                  SCOWL, n.

   1. The wrinkling of the brows in frowning; the expression of
   displeasure, sullenness or discontent in the countenance.

   2. Gloom; dark or rude aspect; as of the heavens.
